label chapter11:

    # [Scene: Rooftop Farm Terraces | Golden Hour]

    scene bg ch11_e67f19_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, hopeful strings with light percussion]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant gulls; the soft hiss of drip irrigation; neighborhood voices carried on the breeze]
    "The relocation program is underway—houses shifted, new hubs rising on higher ground, and the terraces themselves are a kind of proof: patched tarps folded into awnings, rain-catchment cisterns humming, tomatoes and salt-tolerant greens spiking toward the"
    "sun. You smell damp soil warmed by morning light and the faint electrical tang of LEDs used to train a stubborn patch of experimental moss."
    "Rafi kneels by a tray, palms dark with peat. He looks up, grinning, the exact same boy you argued lab protocol with years ago—if the years had been busier and the grin a little softer at the edges."
    show rafi_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_chen "Okay, okay—look. Bioluminescent moss as a light-path. Low energy, locally grown, and, yes, it looks like something out of a children's book, but it's also practical."
    "You feel something in your chest unclench. The light is ridiculous and small and immediately like a promise."
    show maya_armitage at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "Rafi—it's beautiful. But how reliable? Nights here get muddy fast; we can't have people stumbling where the tide took streets last year."

    rafi_chen "Right. It's a pilot. We'll layer it with reflectors and low rails. The moss signals the route; lanterns back up the gaps. And—' (he leans in, voice confidential) '—if it actually encourages folks to walk the route at night, that social glue is worth more than a thousand grant reports."
    "Jonah Reyes is nearby, hands tucked into his vest pockets, watching the moss like it's a small boat he wants to take to sea. He tucks his chin, half-smile working at the corner of his mouth."
    show jonah_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "My younger cousin would love this. Kids will call it the glow-bridge and drag you into every night game you can imagine, Rafi."

    rafi_chen "That's the point. We stitch things back together—literal and metaphorical."
    "You run a finger along the moss tray's edge. The little leaves brush your skin, damp and cool, and the light seems to warm as soon as you touch it. Your notebook is in your back"
    "pocket, pages full of logistics and permits; this feels like a gentle rebellion against the sterile rows of those pages."

    menu:
        "Get your hands in—help Rafi plant a trial row":
            "You roll up your sleeves and kneel. Mud presses between your fingers. Rafi grins as you place the first plugs; Jonah hums a quick rhythm while you work. The act is small, physical, and immediate—hope that feels like elbow grease."
        "Step back—ask for a durability report first":
            "You cross your arms and ask technical questions, and Rafi answers with numbers. The mood becomes less like a campfire and more like a planning meeting; the moss still glows, but the room's warmth shifts toward caution. Jonah watches you—respectful, a little concerned."

    # --- merge ---
    "The terrace fills with that practical tenderness you know well—hands doing the work, minds making exceptions for dreams."

    rafi_chen "Both approaches matter. You bring the field sense; the durability report gives the mayor less reason to say no."
    "The terrace fills with that practical tenderness you know well—hands doing the work, minds making exceptions for dreams. Nan's voice carries from the slope below, a thread of the old story and the new."
    hide rafi_chen
    show gracie_nan_armitage at left:
        zoom 0.7

    gracie_nan_armitage "If lights keep the path, then we'll have ceremony at night again—bring back lantern prayers."
    "You let the thought sit. Ceremony stitched into adaptation. It tastes like the salt air on your tongue: bitter and bright at once."
    # [Scene Transition: The terrace breeze carries you down toward the marsh]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Footsteps on wooden planks; distant splashes as someone tests a new floating planter]
    # [Scene: Reclaimed Marsh | Dawn]
    hide maya_armitage
    hide jonah_reyes
    hide gracie_nan_armitage

    scene bg ch11_e67f19_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse harp plucks; steady undercurrent of wind through reeds]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Frogs half-asleep; the soft scrub of knitting needles; the murmur of neighbors exchanging condolences and plans]
    "The memorial planting has brought a crowd: elders wrapped in shawls, schoolchildren with gloves too big for their hands, friends who have come to show support. You move through them and feel the tug of a"
    "hundred small obligations—the promise to those who can still teach you how the marsh used to breathe, the responsibility to keep those teachings alive even if the land changes shape."
    "Gracie Nan stands by the edge of a planting bed, her hands in wet soil. Her face has that patient, weathered line heroes in old stories have: sympathy that knows how to keep working."
    show gracie_nan_armitage at left:
        zoom 0.7

    gracie_nan_armitage "We can keep a place for the prayers, Maya. But not if we stiffen and refuse to learn new maps. People are tired of telling their children the old names. They want new stories too."
    "An older man—one of the fishermen who used to trade for twice as much fish as his boat now brings in—speaks up, voice thick."

    "Elder Fisher" "But naming the place, keeping the stones—those are how we remember. We move the houses, yes, but don't take our altars. You can't guard a memory with tarps."
    "You stand between them, both literal and metaphorical. The crowd's eyes find you on reflex—you're both a maker of tables and the one who must help them decide which wood to use."
    show maya_armitage at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "We will preserve the ceremonial nodes where they can remain meaningful. But we have to think about safety—some sites flood too often to be practical. There are ways to honor the old without endangering people."
    "The exchange is soft but full of friction. An elder's hand clamps your shoulder for a moment—not accusatory, but rooted."

    "Elder Fisher" "We ask that you don't put a dollar sign on our stories."
    "Jonah Reyes steps forward, steady as a mooring line. His voice is gentle but firm."
    show jonah_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "We're not selling them. We're finding ways to keep them standing together. If the marsh becomes a hall for memory, then the people around it can lean on it, not be crushed by it."
    "Your internal ledger does the impossible: it lets compassion and pragmatism sit side by side. You hear the marsh breathe; it is fragile, but life is pushing back—small birds threading channels newly formed."
    # [Scene: Meeting Tent | Late Afternoon]
    hide gracie_nan_armitage
    hide maya_armitage
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch11_e67f19_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low piano; optimistic but with steady tension]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Papers shuffling; murmured negotiations; a coffee urn hissing softly]
    "The meeting fills up quickly—Mayor Lena, Rafi, community elders, a smattering of young adults, Jonah Reyes, and then Evelyn Hart, immaculate even in the tent's flapping constraints. Her trench coat is somehow still precise; her eyes, as always, unreadable."
    show evelyn_hart at left:
        zoom 0.7

    evelyn_hart "I've negotiated a compensation clause that buys investors into whole-street acquisitions. In exchange, we can guarantee legally binding protections for families we relocate—funds for relocation, access to services, and a commitment to COIN (Community-Operated Infrastructure Network) maintenance."
    "Her words are crisp; for a moment, they sit like ice in the air. The clause is displayed: glossy, dense. It smells faintly of printer ink and the polished promise of big plans."
    "You read it quickly—no time for the microscopic parsing that keeps you awake at night. The clause looks like security on paper and like possibility at the same time."
    "Gracie Nan folds her hands in her lap, eyes narrowing. Jonah Reyes's jaw tightens; he presses his thumb into the seam of his palm. Rafi angles his head, already thinking of how the clause would change funding flows for his projects."
    show jonah_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "Evelyn, you're asking us to trade whole streets. Streets with names. Streets with people."

    evelyn_hart "I'm asking us to secure outcomes you want. Immediate housing, legal guarantees, resources for the schools. The alternative is slow funding and the real risk that investors walk."
    show maya_armitage at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "But uncertainty isn't the same as bad faith. If a trust can legally protect cultural nodes and ensure relocated families don't become footnotes—"

    evelyn_hart "It might. Or it might scare investors away, and then no protections happen because there are no funds."
    "Jonah Reyes interrupts, not unkindly but with the force of someone done watching promises evaporate."

    jonah_reyes "We need to protect people now. If investors walk, what then? People sleep under tarps. Kids miss another school term. Which suffering do you choose?"

    evelyn_hart "We choose the one that gets a solution on the ground the fastest. We do not have the luxury of time that long processes assume."
    "Your mind catalogs the options like a scientist (as it always insists on doing): immediate resources with strings, a trust that binds capital to community ideals but delays relief, or refusing to give in and improvising together. Each path has warmth and risk."
    "A younger organizer at the end of the table—someone you recognize from the terrace—speaks with blunt honesty."

    "Young Organizer" "Accepting redevelopment feels like selling our stories to the highest bidder. But leaving folks without roofs is worse."
    "The tent holds its breath. Outside, the marsh glints in the late afternoon sun—white light and dark water braided like an argument."

    menu:
        "Call for a temporary pause—form a committee to draft a trust option":
            "You suggest a pause and propose a committee composed of elders, youth, and legal counsel to draft a trust. The room hums with cautious approval. Rafi nods like he's been given a chance to buy time for technical work; Jonah places his hand over yours, a small anchor."
        "Push to accept Evelyn's clause now for immediate protections":
            "You emphasize urgent needs and the guarantee clause's benefits. Faces shift—some relieved, some wary. Gracie Nan gives you a look that is complex, not a yes or no, and you feel the weight of choosing speed over ceremony."

    # --- merge ---
    "Evelyn watches the exchange with that steady, calculating gaze. She does not smile often, but when she does it's efficient—an arched concession, a bargaining signal."

    evelyn_hart "Whatever we choose, we structure it to minimize harm. The investors can be partners, not masters. If the town insists on oversight, then oversight will be written into the contracts."
    "You sense the mayor's eyes on you again. There is trust there, a question dressed as expectation."
    hide evelyn_hart
    show mayor_lena_ortiz at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_lena_ortiz "We have to decide strategy today. Funds are in motion. People are already relocating."
    "Your pulse quickens—not from fear, but because this is the moment of stitching. The town needs a thread that won't snap under strain, and your hands are used to mending."
    "Rafi pushes his glasses up and says, quietly, 'There's a creative middle ground. Trusts can be seeded by staged redevelopment—structured so that culture funds are the first allocation. If we can get the clause to guarantee that flow to a community trust, we get resources without total sale.'"
    hide jonah_reyes
    show evelyn_hart at right:
        zoom 0.7

    evelyn_hart "That sounds like a negotiation point. It could work if investors see the mechanism as a safeguard rather than a choke."
    "Jonah Reyes looks at you. His voice is soft, private enough that the tent seems to shrink around him and you."
    hide maya_armitage
    show jonah_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "What do you want, Maya? What's the thing you can't let go of?"
    "You feel all the reasons for your work—Nan's stories, the marsh's salt, the quiet nights you spent on a roof counting stars you could no longer name—gather into a single, coherent slice of will. You want"
    "the people protected. You want the songs kept. You want to hold both at once."
    "Your answer is complicated. It must be. And it must be chosen."
